| Massive Cave Found on Mars                                         |
|   from the anybody-home dept.                                      |
|   posted by Zonk on Thursday June 07, @12:32 (Mars)                |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/07/1520248      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]mrcgran writes "Space.com is reporting [1]a very deep hole found on
Mars: 'The geological oddity measures some 330 feet (100 meters) across
and is [2]located on an otherwise bright dusty lava plain to the
northeast of [3]Arsia Mons, one of the four giant Tharsis volcanoes on
the red planet. The Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter (MRO) used its High
Resolution Imaging Science Experiment (HiRISE) instrument to draw a bead
on the apparent deep hole — a feature that may cause more scientists to
ponder about potential subsurface biology on Mars. Because the spot lacks
a raised rim or tossed out material called ejecta, researchers have ruled
out the pit being an impact crater. No walls or other details can be seen
inside the hole, and so any possible walls might be perfectly vertical
and extremely dark or — more likely — overhanging.' The [4]original image
and [5]its cutout at full resolution can be found in the [6]HiRISE site."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/07/1520248

Links:
    0. http://mgran.blogspot.com/
    1. http://www.space.com/scienceastronomy/070605_mars_hole.html
    2. http://www.google.com/mars/#lat=-5.5&lon=241.4&zoom=6
    3. http://www.google.com/mars/#lat=3.864254&lon=-119.882812&zoom=2&q=arsia%20mons
    4. http://hirise.lpl.arizona.edu/PSP_003647_1745
