| Moore's Law for Motherboards                                       |
|   from the soon-they'll-be-skull-implantable dept.                 |
|   posted by Zonk on Thursday June 07, @13:11 (Portables)           |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/07/1629223     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "VIA CEO Wenchi Chen revealed a [0]business
card-sized motherboard billed as the 'world's first industry-standard
form-factor for PC/phone convergence,' at Computex this week. The
mobile-ITX" board measures 3 x 1.8 inches. It's half the size of
[1]pico-ITX, which was half the size of [2]nano-ITX, which, in turn, was
half-the size of [3]mini-ITX — which was already small. It's not clear
whether VIA will make these tiny motherboards available to end users, or
if they will only be sold directly to device makers, but generally all of
VIA's tiny motherboard formats have spread around to other suppliers and
become widely available."

